description.text: This is a halloween pumpkin model, please print it, I'd love to see your print attempts!

Printer:

XYZ Davinci 1.0a

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

Doesn't matter, 15% is a good number

Notes:

Prints upright, support should not be needed

Create a form in fusion 360

You start off by creating a form in Fusion 360, then you mess around getting the general shape of a pumpkin correct. But remember, you don't want something that has too much overhang and that's easy to get with curves, as it doesn't print well. Make sure your printer can handle the overhangs.

Slicing

Next, you slice the form into sections, I did this by extruding around it with the cut function until I got a nice wedge of the form. I then curved the edges with a fillet, to get the bumpy part you want to see on a pumpkin

Pattern!

Go to create, and then create a pattern. You want this pattern to be a circular pattern, and you want to make the axis in the middle of the wedge, so the wedge creates a pattern of itself around the center point. This will create the basic shape for your pumpkin! Choose as many amounts as you'd like, until it looks like a pumpkin.

Using another feature! The stalk

Create a curved line, and then switch to the patch UI. You want to go to create and extrude this line, so you get yourself a curved face. Then go to create then thicken to make a curved rectangular object! Then you'll need to fillet the edges to soften it up. Then combine it with the pumpkin.

It's up to you if you want to do a stand, which is simply an extruded circle with a fillet, or you could just print it as is! I designed it with a stand because it's easier to print, and looks fancy.

How to Thermoform, Assemble, and String

Unlimbited Arm Release (thermoforming):
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=369PX9LzUPs
Unlimbited Arm Stringing:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nIHpqqgybss

Enable the Future is an organization that creates 3D-printed, upper-limb prosthetics for those in need. It began from an idea Ivan Owen had in 2011 to create a steam punk hand for a convention he was attending. From here, people began to stem off from his original home video on how to build the hand and thus 3D printing of prosthetics was born. This website provides open source files and the means to link up a volunteer to someone in need of a prosthetic. Recipients are typically impoverished and cannot afford to receive a prosthetic by other means or are children who quickly outgrow prosthetics provided to them. 3D printing prosthetics is a quick and cheap alternative that does not sacrifice too much efficiency.
Of the many prosthetics available on this website, the Unlimbited Arm – Alfie Edition was chosen to be built for this project. How it works is the Unlimbited Arm mimics the tendons in a real hand. The strings that run along the underneath of the hand functioning to close the hand are equivalent to flexor tendons whose job is to pull back on the joint. The rubber bands on the knuckles of the prosthetic functioning to bring the hand back to the open position are akin to the extensor tendons whose job is to straighten or extend the joint. Instead of these artificial tendons being attached to muscles, they are strung all the way through the prosthetic reaching the elbow where mechanical forces of the arm bending create a tension force that should pull the fingers down.
3D printing utilizes Fused Deposition Modeling to construct three-dimensional objects. This process sends specific controls to the controller head which functions to release melted plastic accordingly. Each melted layer is laid based on specific coordinates and cooled by fans or the environment to solidify it. There are three main plastics that are used as filaments for 3D printing: ABS, PLA, and Nylon. PLA is the recommend filament for the construction of Enable the Future’s prosthetic.

1. Make 3 measurements on my left arm: bicep circumference, forearm length, and hand length.
  2. Generate the STL files based on these measurements in Thingiverse Customizer and download them.
  3. Determine the best filament to use based on characteristics and thermoforming ability (PLA is best because ABS has to be super hot to thermoform and this is hard to do without the proper equipment).
  4. Translate each STL into a code the MakerBot replicator plus can read using the software MakerBot Print. While in MakerBot Print, manipulate how dense the pieces are and how they print based on enablethefuture’s quality specifications. Also take into consideration what would print faster with less supports without sacrificing quality of the print.
  5. With the 7 pieces printed in PLA and the assembly kit, construct the prosthetic following tutorials and use thermoforming to bend pieces that are supposed to be curved.

I USED the following measurements for my arm:
PinHoleDia = 5 (increase pin size to what looks appropriate for arm)
CuffLength = 65 (leave as is)
BicepCircum = 322 ( based on affected arm)
HandLen = 174 (based on unaffected hand)
ForearmLen = 238 (based on unaffected forearm)
LeftRight = Left

Tricks I Learned While Printing This

-Don't allow any draft of air to hit the glow-in-the-dark filament otherwise your print will fail
-If there are random fibers are your print, you can sand down (along the grain not against it) with 200 grit sandpaper
-Thermoform carefully or the layers may begin to split
-Thermoform extremely accurately or the pins that you put in after may not fit/stay
-I put supports on everything just to be safe
-an Adult length forearm will not fit flat into the replicator + bed so you may have to pint at an angle with supports
-the screw can easily strip the tensor pins so adjust with caution (you may also want to print more just in case)
-superglue the gel fingertips down as well as the knots made during stringing

Je trouve que le ressort livré avec l'extrudeur est difficile à serrer, d'autant que le passage du fil ne se fait pas toujours ou on voudrait...
Donc, j'ai imaginé ce petit levier, qui permet d'enfiler le fil plus facilement.
Il est compatible avec le guide-fil que tout le monde connaît et utilise (recherchez "Creality CR-10 Filament Guide", merci à Greg191134).

Il est essentiel d'imprimer 100% de remplissage, et avec des couche de 0.1, en raison de l'emmanchement du le levier dans l'axe. Je n'ai pas fait de post-traitement, mis à part un ébavurage rapide et une goutte d'huile entre l'axe et le support. Imprimé avec du filament Octofiber.
Attention, une fois le levier clippé dans l'axe, il est presque impossible de le démonter.

Bien sûr, vous devrez trouver une tête hexa M3 x 25 à vis cylindrique en acier inoxydable. Mais notre copain Aliexpress est là, pour ça, n'est-ce pas?

2017/11/12: remix: nouveau support arrondi avec support câble

I find that the spring of the standard extruder is difficult to maintain, especially because the loading of the filament does not always happens as you would like ...
So, I imagined this small lever, which allows to pass the filament easily.
It is compatible with the filament guide that a lot of users know and use (search for "Creality CR-10 Filament Guide", Thanks to Greg191134).

It is essential to print at 100% infill, and layer 0.1, because of the fitting between the lever and the axis. I did'nt do any post treatment, except for a quick deburring and a drop of oil between the axis and the support. Printed with Octofiber filament.
Carefull! Once you clip the lever into the axis, it will be very difficult to separate them...

Of course, you will have to find a stainless steel screw, cylindrical head hexa M3 x 25. But our buddy Aliexpress is there, is'nt it ?.

This is a spacer set to allow an IR lens to be placed inside of a 7x zoom lens without having to glue it in place. a spacer is placed on either side of a spring, which holds the IR lens in place. I used a spring (clipped in half) from a bag of springs purchased at microcenter.

description.text: A simple RV. Prints best in carbon fiber. The red disc inserts into the other part for a neat 2 color look.

I simply use standard 3 mil glass cut at a hardware store on my print bed. As such they are rarely cut to a tight enough tolerance to have it just drop snuggly into stationary corner brackets.

This bracket design uses 3mm x 8mm dia neodymium magnets which quickly snap to conform to the glass edges. By using a couple of 3d printed clips I have a fast and low profile glass mounting system that doesn't require glass to be precision cut. Drop the glass on. Clip up the corners which squares things up and snap on a couple of printed clips.

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:311665

If I'm printing a large print with a lot of mass I will add large metal paper clips for extra insurance but for most smaller prints this arrangement has proven to be sufficient.

Press in magnets with a small application of CA glue. Press in a 3mm nut. Run bed screw down through assembly and snug to bed. Install spring. Install wingnut.

Probably best printed in ABS for longevity as with all these clamping devices used on a heated bed.

title: Comic Book Wall Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I wanted a wall hanger that used 3m command poster strips(or similar), was quick and easy to print, had a low profile(so not to distract from the comics it would be displaying), and allows me to swap/pull comics with only minimal effort. These are the two designs I came up with.
The regular is meant to be printed on the thin side with the long side on the 'Z'. This way you can pack a large amount into a small area(see picture above). The Lite version I have always printed with the "ears" flat on the bed.

Both of these are made to use unmodified 3M command poster strips. You can get them cheap in bulk online but in case money is tight I have tried other double sided sticky things but they may have to be modified to fit the hangers. I have also successfully used a poster strip cut long ways in half on my wall hangers with no fall off issues what so ever(hanging loaded with comics for 3 months+). I have even done it with one strip in the middle but I don't recommend it because if you are a little heavy handed loading your comics onto them or pull it off at an odd angle, it goes out of level(also very wobbly since it only has one point of contact) . I prefer to use two full poster strips because it's easier. I apply the "poster" sticky side to the mount and the "wall" side to the wall(easy right?)

I have yet to come home and have a comic on the floor or randomly fall off their hangers. They lean back far enough that most breezes haven't disturbed them. I currently have twenty seven comics hanging on my walls with the various holders I have designed/printed and they have been there for a few months with no fall or drop issues.

The hangers in the mid-right/upper-right of my picture are from my first design which was basically an equilateral triangle with a hook on it. They functioned just fine but I wasn't happy with the visual footprint especially if I would have to change color to print more. So I made these updated ones to have a much smaller visual footprint which allows the use of various colors and not impact the look as much. Also with the bracket tucked behind and up, it can allow you to closely mount the comics if you wanted to fit more in a smaller area.

After designing a couple of bobbins in Tinkercad...
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2579262
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2528103
... I realized that it would be fairly easy to make an OpenSCAD customizer for spinning wheel bobbins so that you just enter some parameters and it produces the parts required to make the bobbin. As with the Tinkercad designs, the parts are in a modular format that fit together fairly snugly and are easy to print.
If supports are required, they're very small/simple and they're always on an inside face. And much of the time you can just print the piece upside-down to avoid the need for supports.

The default parameters are for a Schacht standard bobbin. If that is what you want, you can go to the Thing I created here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2586323
I've also used this to make a customized Majacraft standard bobbin, which you can find here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2586421
You can find the specific parameters for those bobbins in the individual Thing details, but I also give some custom parameters for various bobbins later in this Thing's description.

To generate your own custom bobbin, you start by clicking on the "Open in Customizer" button above. Through the customizer you specify measurements for your spinning wheel bobbin and generate your own custom Thing with that data.

The "Parts" tab lets you select a specific part of the bobbin you want to view or it lets you select "all" to display the entire bobbin as it would be assembled. This is only affects what you view in the customizer -- when you generate a new Thing it will create all of the parts.
In this modular bobbin design, it is typical that several pieces will not be used as part of the final bobbin. (For example, you might not have a second whorl or any whorl at all on one of the ends.) Parts that are not used still have to be generated, and their content will contain a simple "unused" text string. You can delete these when your custom design is created.
Note that the "all" part is also created and is intended for display purposes only -- it is not practical to try to print this all in once piece.

The "Core and Mandrel" tab lets you specify dimensions for the bobbin core (length and diameter) and for the mandrel diameter (shaft bore hole size). It also lets you set the distance the core is recessed into the ends.

The "Front End Main" and "Back End Main" tabs specify the geometry of the main part of the bobbin ends: their height (thickness) and diameter, and whether or not there is a groove and how wide/deep it is. Additionally, you can set whether a bushing component will extrude from the end (on top of any whorls you might add).
Don't put too much thought into the "Front" and "Back" names -- it is just a label and they are treated the same in the design. If you're replicating an existing bobbin you can pick either end as the starting point.

Most bobbins have one or more whorls -- a component with a groove for a drive band. The various whorl tabs let you specify the geometry of the whorls -- their height (thickness), diameter, the location of the groove, and its width / depth.

The "Advanced" tab mostly allows you to adjust tolerances of various aspects of the design. You can also set how curved the main parts of the ends and whorls appear.

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2586323

description.text:
A simple E3Dv6 Chimera/Cyclops mount, that is quick to print, lightweight and basic tolerances. Recommended for use with mechanical endstops, but remixes for BL Touch or capacitive sensor are welcome. The included belt clip should fit snug between your x axis bearing blocks. Please post your makes, I'd love to see what you do with this!

UPDATE 11/9/2017

The upper brace for the mount on the carriage (Where you screw in) was too thin in my opinion, it seemed too easy to warp, so I have modified the design further, increasing the thickness of this plate, so it isn't prone to any form of heat warp. Enjoy!

Also added an untested dual 40mm fan duct mount, it should work just fine, but I have yet to print the dual duct mount and try it out myself. I'll likely have an update soon on this. However, do print at your own risk as I have not tried it myself.

Please note, supports are not completely necessary, but are recommended to avoid any sagging in vertical holes. I set my support angle to 50 degrees to minimize the amount of supports generated.

Tinkercad

Please note I did not completely design the carriage, and I did not design the fan duct. For whatever reason, I CANNOT find the source carriage/designer who originally made this. Basically I added some holes and cut some angles off of the carriage to minimize the weight and amount of plastic required to print, I also added the triangular vertical supports to add rigidity, and added some thickness to the plate you screw the hotend to. The duct sits perfectly next to the cyclops/chimera and the base designs tolerances and simplicity were the reason for my choosing this design to modify and use on my own printer. Shoutout to the original designer, you did a great job.

title: MP Select Mini V2 Exhaust Cover

description.text:
I noticed when my bed slides to the full back position it has trouble maintaining temperatures needed for ABS. I placed my hand under the bed and noticed air from the chassis fan was hitting the underside of the bed. At first, I just bent a piece of cardboard in a half circle and set it between the fan and the bed. Then I got the bright idea to print something a bit classier. Unless you are close to a back wall, this will keep the chassis fan from cooling the bed.

The internal fan is only supported by the 4 visible screws. If you put this on, be sure to have at least one screw in the fan at all times, otherwise it may fall inside, making installation a lot more difficult than it needs be.

title: HEVO Mount for the Nimble and a V6

description.text:
An Hypercube Evo mount that combines a E3D V6 and the Zesty Nimble into a compact direct drive solution for the HEVO.

It uses the standard blower and duct to cool the printed part, and the standard fan for the V6.

The mount is attached to the X carriage the standard way, with 4 dowel pins and the insert.
The clamp uses 2x M3x25 screws and nuts to clamp the V6. The Nimble uses the standard supplied screws and the BT Touch bracket uses a M3x12 mm screw and nut to attach to the main mount.

Edit: A mount for the standard induction sensor is now available as well.

Edit 2: It seems I needed to make more space for the optical sensors. Thanks Bartolomeus! I have added some space there. That is the only change for V1.1

Edit 3: Added a IR sensor mount for the DC42 differential IR sensor board. It is a bit of a flat block, but should print fine. I added a stiffening rib to make it a little less floppy.
Also added a plain shape for a DIY sensor mount, so you can design your own.

The BL Touch mount has a sliding rail system to allow for fine tuning up and down. The bracket CAD file can be used to modify the bracket to fit any other sensor. If you have a specific sensor you want to mount, just let me know in the comments and I will add it.

Edit 4: Added a main mount that is changed in the following ways: The BL Touch is mounted on the other side, the original position took too much X space. Also, the mount is no longer fixed with pins and inserts, but simple bolts going through and through. Meaning you will need to use a carriage that has space for nuts on the inside.

Edit 5: Added a mount that has a captive M3 nut in the base, instead of the inserts. For the rest no changes.

As always, any comments, suggestions and such are welcome.

The STL models are checked and optimised. The parts that need a different orientation to print properly are rotated to the preferred printing position.

The Nimble Extruder

Laser cut stand for 6 X 10 addressable RGB LEDs.

I recently purchased a 3.2ft string of WS2812 addressable RGB LEDs to play with. They can be cut at certain points along the tape to make a strip as long or short as you want. Or you can jumper together multiple strings to make a longer unit.

Since a wiggly coil of flashing lights on my bench didn't appeal to me, I decided to cut them apart and make a 6 X 10 matrix (this strip had 60 LEDs on it). I was going to 3D print a mount of some type, but figured this might be a good time to whip out the ol' laser engraver/cutter and put it to use.

I designed a simple mount for the lights in SketchUp to make sure everything was going to fit together, and then simplified the drawing for export to a DXF file, which is easily imported into my laser software. I'm using the latest build of LaserWeb (4.0.990) to control the laser.

I used 3mm birch plywood for my material. My laser is only 7W, so I made 2 passes at 75% power, moving at 100mm/min. It cut through 99% cleanly, requiring only a small amount of exactoing to get a few of the pieces out.

The board for the LED's slides into the 3 stands and then 2 cross braces are slid into place and locked down. This allows the whole thing be broken down and stored in a compact manner. Everything could be glued for a permanent fixture.

Once everything was cut out, I cut the LED strip apart and stuck them to the backingboard using the sticky tape that comes on them. Then wired them up, and slid the board into the stand and installed the cross braces.

The whole things is about the size of a small tablet, and is easy to place next to a breadboard on my bench.

In addition to using a stand alone Arduino to drive the matrix, I've also been playing with a PC based peice of software called "Glediator". It's basically a DJ mixing board for lights. It was a pain to get talking to the Arduino UNO, but works pretty well once the PC and UNO start talking (hint: if using an x64 PC, install the x32 RXTX).

The UNO can power this small matrix without issue, but if you build a bigger one, you may want to run power directly to the LED's.

title: gripstruder 4x the grip force, in many cases this means extruding prints  at over 800mm/m of 1.75mm feedstock

description.text:
this is to be called the 'gripstruder' for its exceptional griping of feedstock.
12/1/2014:
recent addition of file xt5.stl , that has support that needs cut away, it deals with prolong use fatigue, and unifies lever pulley arm. best if level arm that holds bearings is made of ABS. other parts PLA is ok, just so much stress load is on arm that head cycles from motor heat tend to wear the original part out, abs is more graceful. part hinge is bolt of motor, and other parts are not under stress of load where it heats up. video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZcHtu8XVnBk&feature=youtu.be i have uploaded a part called mount_withbolton, it is an update that has bolt holes to fit on seemecnc mount plate
requires 2 608 bearings, a 2inch 6/32 bolt, 2 washers, a high compression spring, and a 3mm flat heat bolt about 6mm in length, and a flat head 6/32 1 inch long phillips bolt. then whatever bolts you use to mount to your motor, also requires a bowden metal grip likely from seemecnc. this design was inspired for faster printing with my rostock max delta bot. this design allows for strong grip of feedstock and 4 times the surface area to grip as normal extruder pinch grips. the mechanism that holds feedstock is the pressure between two 608 bearings, each bearing has twice the contact surface of the R2ZZ bearing, and then there are 2 of them. this allows 4 times the surface area to apply pressure, meaning more force can be applied and feedstock will not reshape. I have tested this extruder design up to 800mm/m flow rates.

take the bottom part of the idler, push onto it two 608 bearings. there is a built in groove surface to allow outside of bearing to rotate freely. then take the top idler part, and a flat head 3mm or 6/32 screw and thread it thru the top part, and then thru the bottom part, then take a 3mm flat heat bolt and thread and screw it into the round part of the idler. the idea is that the idler should come together as one piece and have little play.  
after this take the big idler block and mount it to a motor, then take a 8mm gear hobbled mount and place it on the motor shaft. slide feedstock thru and let the motor mount fit where it should based on the position of the feedstock. be sure the grub screw completely sinks into the hobbled gear mount on the motor shaft so it does not rotate around and get caught by the bottom bearing.  
place the idler arm inside the screw mount as it has the strength to support the arm, then place a bolt long enough thru the bottom of the motor mount screw hole, and thru the idler screw hole. then place a washer, a high compression spring, and another washer and a nut at the end. keep it loose for now. then seemecnc idlers include a metal mount to go to bowden extruders. this mount snaps into place with pliers. be careful not to tear the plastic, i gripped the top side by the metal, and the bottom by channel locks. make sure the holes are unobstructed, i used a small but long screwdriver that had a 2mm shaft and worked it thru the metal part, and the plastic and thru the other side. you want feedstock to move freely but not to buckle.  
i have included images, and will update instructions more later. enjoy!

title: Arduino Nano base for Minecraft diamond ore lamp

description.text:
So this isn't a re-mix of the cube itself; it's a base I designed that has holes for 4 round 6.9mm thread push button momentary switches like these:

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0752RMB7Q/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1

There is also a slot for an arduino nano (it's a modified version of emccarron nano mounting base); you just set the nano in the channel, and then push it forward towards the usb hole so that the side near the usb hole is locked down. The front side of the arduino needs to be locked down with 2 blobs of hot glue (thee wasn't enough room for a channel to slide the entire nano in like in emccarron's design).

Note the USB hole is oriented with the Nano facing down; this is so that the nano's power LED is facing down, and will not cast it's red glow up into the minecraft cube.

The post in the center is just there to be a place to hot glue the LED to.

For my arduino sketch, I'm simply using an RGB fader so that colors can be blended by pushing the Red, Green, & Blue buttons; it's similar to this sketch from this adafruit tutorial (and this sketch will indeed work):

https://learn.adafruit.com/adafruit-arduino-lesson-3-rgb-leds

The black button is a reset button to reset the arduino which turns the lights off. One side of the switch you run to the reset pin on the aduino, another to ground.

title: Hictop Prusa I3 E3D V6 Carriage

description.text:
This is a ground up build that includes all of my favorite modifications for the X-Carriage of my HIctop Prusa I3. It mounts an E3D V6 hot end, converts the hotend cooler and part cooler from axial 40mm fans to 5015 radial fans (drastically improving cooling), and relocates the bed level sensor to the front with provisions for an adjustable height mount. I've included updated firmware that compensates for the relocation, changes bed leveling to 4x4 bilinear, optimizes PID gains and significantly smooths movement along all axes. YOU WILL NEED TO INSULATE YOUR HOTEND IF YOU PLAN TO USE THE PART COOLER FAN IN THIS CARRIAGE

*NOTE** LCD SCREEN FUNCTIONALITY IS GREATLY REDUCED. THIS FIRMWARE IS VERY MUCH A WORK IN PROGRESS HOWEVER WILL PRINT VERY WELL USING EXTERNAL SOFTWARE LIKE OCTOPRINT/ASTROPRINT ETC.

This is a remix of the awesome 100 counter. i use specifically for star realms but this can be used for tracking anything with less than 100 hp.

Changes.

Made the back piece thicker
Made the holes in the dial bigger so they fit the front and back pieces
Added a "clicker" so each number clicks and kinda barely locks in so that the numbers dont spin free and you can pick it up without the numbers changing.

I play with cheaters and the clicker makes it harder for someone to accidentally change their HP. lol!

If you want colored numbers printed print the dials seperate and change the filament on layer 9 or at 1.8-1.9mm if your slicer cant pause at layers. You dont really even need a pause. as soon as you see it start to barely print the numbers on the dial if you are fast enough just do a "hot swap" while its printing. thats what i do.

I printers at 100% fill and .2 with pla
infill and materials dont matter.

description.text:
Here's a small adapter that lets you adapt an Intertap stout nozzle (eg https://www.morebeer.com/products/intertap-stout-spout.html) To a common polypropylene picnic faucet (https://www.morebeer.com/products/hand-held-beer-faucet.html) to make a cheap and portable stout faucet.

I made this for serving up nitro cold brew coffee, but it might come in handy for beer :)

Print the adapter using PETG with a 0.05mm (suggested) layer height without supports. There's a fairly big overhang angle on the threads, and the thread pitch is only ~1.4mm, so the thinner layer height is needed for sufficiently good threads.

I used black MG Chemicals PETG. Technically it's not food grade but I'm not too worried - if the SDS says I can pretty much eat the plastic straight up without worrying about toxicity, I have my doubts anything is going to leach out of it and harm me.

To glue the adapter to the spout, first remove the valve from the spout. Rough up the surface of the spout first with fine grit sandpaper for better adhesion. Apply ECA glue (Krazy Glue, Loctite 401, whatever) to the spout and push the adapter onto it, twisting it as you slide it on. Allow it to set for half an hour or so, soak everything in water for another half hour to neutralize any remaining glue, and wash/clean well. Reassemble the spout, attach it to a hose, screw on the stout nozzle and you should be good to go.

OpenSCAD design file is attached. You'll need to grab a copy of OpenSCAD threads from here - http://dkprojects.net/openscad-threads - copy the "threads.scad" file into the same directory as the source file.

description.text:
The Backbone Strap is the solution to loose hanging straps. Use these straps by rolling a loose strap then locking it down with the elastic band. These straps are tough as nails so they won't come off, they leave no sticky residue like tape, and are easy to move or remove.

I actually sell these on my Etsy shop (link below) but I wanted to share my creation with the maker community. You would be surprised to find out that this simple design went through many many revisions.

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00LFSPPOC/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

As a veteran, when out in the field it is mandatory to keep our straps tied down. We used to use either tape or Velcro. But the Velcro always came off, and the tape left a bunch of goo behind. Neither were particularly easy to adjust. After about 20 prototypes I finally came up with the solution you see here. I use this product everyday now and thought I would share it with the world. title: Wheeled bumpers for Onewheel+ and Onewheel V1

description.text:
These are bumpers made to attach 50mm luggage wheels. Put them on the back and add a handle to the front bumper to make it easy to roll the Onewheel like luggage, rather than carry it. It's easy to make a handle by doing something as simple as drilling holes in the front bumper and running paracord through the holes and a grip of some kind. Magnets can hold it to the bottom when not in use.

These bumpers can also be added to the front to protect against nosedives. Keep in mind that wheels would only protect the rider from sudden deceleration caused by the bumper grinding against the ground. If the rider is not well balanced, the nose suddenly dropping out from under the front foot will cause a fall, whether there are wheels or not.

These bumpers are part of a full kit available at Carvepower

There are some narrow slots embedded in the sections that hold the wheels. These are thin enough that they will likely be filled in when printed. If you print with 6 perimeters, the perimeters around the slots will cause those sections to be solid without the need to print the entire bumper at 100% infill.

Add #10-32 heat inserts to the blind holes for attaching the bumper.
